<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF208-216-478  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 216 478.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Design  Nov 9 1989 v37 n23 p30(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>To ensure testable circuits, software embeds scan-path logic.andO;(Guild AMI's NetScan automatic-test-generating software)(Technology Advances)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Bursky, Dave.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Gould AMI has developed the NetScan software that automaticallygenerates test vectors for circuits by inserting scan-path logicinto their designs.andP;  The program reduces design overhead byincreasing run time more or less linearly to keep pace withincreasing gate counts; other test generators increase run timeexponentially.andP;  Gould AMI claims NetScan is the first fullyautomated ASIC test-pattern generator that works with circuit datafrom any computer-aided engineering software package; the programwill generally run with Gould's NetTrans universal netlisttranslator.andP;  The D-algorithm is combined with scan-path designtechniques to generate test vectors for each potentialsingle-stuck-line (SSL) fault in a combinatorial circuit.andP;  Faultsare inserted repeatedly, after which vectors are found betweenfault and fault-free circuit behavior.andP;  Other aspects of NetScan'sdesign are discussed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Gould Inc. Gould AMI (product development).andO;Product:   NetScan (CAE software) (product development).andO;Topic:     Circuit DesignTestingTest Data GeneratorsSoftware PackagesCombinational CircuitsCombinatoricsApplication-specific integrated circuitsComputer-aided engineering.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>